<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="S-mult_int-cylsphere">
  <title>Triple Integrals in Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <!-- <li>
      <p>
      What are the cylindrical coordinates of a point, and how are they related to Cartesian coordinates?
      </p>
      </li> -->
      <li>
        <p>
          What is the volume element in cylindrical coordinates and how do we use this to evaluate a triple integral as an iterated integral in cylindrical coordinates?
        </p>
      </li>
      <!--  <li>
      <p>
      What are the spherical coordinates of a point, and how are they related to Cartesian coordinates?
      </p>
      </li> -->
      <li>
        <p>
          What is the volume element in spherical coordinates and how do we use this to evaluate a triple integral as an iterated integral in spherical coordinates?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <introduction component="instructor">
    <title>Notes to the Instructor and Dependencies</title>
    <p>
      This section generalizes triple integrals to the two most common non-rectangular coordinate systems. Because we introduced these ideas in our precalculus topics, we can be more direct in defining the volume elements for each of these systems and practice the slicing of a volume using these other coordinate systems. Because we have emphasized cylindrical coordinates as <q>polar with <m>z</m></q>, the portion of this section on cylindrical coordinates also provides an opportunity for students to practice their skills with polar coordinates.
    </p>
    <p>
      We feel there is little to be gained in having students <em>evaluate</em> iterated triple integrals except in the simplest of cases. We recommend that instructors emphasize evaluation of <em>double</em> iterated integrals earlier in this chapter so that the focus when discussing triple integrals can be on setting up the integral <em>in the best coordinate system</em>. Thus, the activities in this section provide students with more practice setting up iterated triple integrals in cylindrical and spherical coordinates and only ask them to evaluate one of these integrals.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some instructors give this section a quick coverage as a preview of the next section which will generalize triple integrals into any coordinate system and describe how to transform triple integrals between coordinate systems.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="S-mult_int-polar"/>, we how polar coordinates can provide a simpler way to write iterated integrals when trying to evaluate a double integral. Double integrals with integrands and regions of integration that are simple to write in polar coordinates are the most convenient to convert, as long as care is taken with the area element, which is <m>dA = r\,  dr \, d\theta</m> when using polar coordinates.
    </p>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="S-Precalc-OtherCoordSystems"/>, we introduced the cylindrical and spherical coordinate systems and explored converting points, equations, and regions between these and rectangular coordinate systems in three dimensions. Cylindrical coordinates are most commonly used in situations with rotational symmetry around the <m>z</m>-axis, while spherical coordinates are primarily used when there is rotational symmetry around the origin. You may find it useful to review the <xref ref="Cartesian-cylindrical" text="custom">conversion equations between cylindrical and rectangular coordinates</xref> and <xref ref="Spherical-rect" text="custom">conversion equations between spherical and rectangular coordinates</xref>. This section's Preview Activity asks you to think about some common surfaces in cylindrical or spherical coordinates before starting to use them for triple integrals.
    </p>
    <worksheet>
      <exploration workspace="1.5in">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            For each surface below, first sketch a plot by hand of the surface described. Then write a couple of sentences describing how your plot relates to the cylindrical or spherical coordinates used to describe the surface.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in cylindrical coordinates by <m>r=2</m>, <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>, and <m>0 \leq z \leq 2</m>. 
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              In polar coordinates, the graph of <m>r=2</m> is a circle centered at the origin with radius 2. Extending this to cylindrical coordinates, we obtain a cylinder centered at the origin of radius 2, with base on the <m>xy</m>-plane and height 2.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in cylindrical coordinates by <m>r=2</m>, <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \pi</m>, and <m>0 \leq z \leq 2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in cylindrical coordinates by <m>\theta=2</m>, <m>0 \leq r \leq 2</m>, and <m>0 \leq z \leq 2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              In polar coordinates, the graph of <m>\theta = 2</m> is a line through the origin making an angle of 2 radians with the positive <m>x</m>-axis. Extending this to cylindrical coordinates,the graph of <m>\theta=2</m> is a plane through the origin perpendicular to the <m>xy</m>-plane making an angle of 2 radians with the <m>xz</m>-plane.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in cylindrical coordinates by <m>z=r</m>, <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>, and <m>0 \leq r \leq 2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              For a fixed value of <m>r</m>, the graph of <m>z=r</m> and <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m> is a circle of radius <m>r</m> in the plane <m>z=r</m>. As <m>r</m> increases the radii increase, so we will obtain a cone with base at the origin, opening up with height <m>2</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in spherical coordinates by <m>\rho = 1</m>, <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>, and <m>0 \leq \phi \leq \pi</m>. 
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>\rho</m> measures the distance from the origin to a point, the graph of <m>\rho = 1</m> is the set of all points that are a distance 1 from the origin. This makes <m>\rho=1</m> the equation of the sphere of radius 1 centered at the origin.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in spherical coordinates by <m>\rho = 1</m>, <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>, and <m>0 \leq \phi \leq \frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The surface described in spherical coordinates by <m>\phi = \frac{\pi}{3}</m>, <m>0 \leq \rho \leq 1</m>, and <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>? 
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              All points with <m>\phi = \frac{\pi}{3}</m> are at a fixed angle from the positive <m>z</m>-axis. The set of such points with <m>0 \leq \rho \leq 1</m> is a cone making an angle of <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m> with the positive <m>z</m>-axis having a slant height of 1.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Write a couple of sentences using the surfaces above to illustrate why we use the names <q>cylindrical coordinates</q> and <q>spherical coordinates</q> for these coordinate systems.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exploration>
    </worksheet>
    <p>
      In this section, we will look at converting triple integrals to use cylindrical and spherical coordinates and similar to our approach in <xref ref="S-mult_int-polar"/>. Just as with writing a double integral in polar coordinates, there are three essential steps to writing a triple integral in cylindrical or spherical coordinates:
      <ol>
        <li>Convert the volume element <m>dV</m> to the new coordinate system.</li>
        <li>Describe the region of integration by using inqualities involving the variables of the new coordinate system.</li>
        <li>Write the integrand <m>f(x,y,z)</m> using the new coordinate system.</li>
      </ol>
      We begin with cylindrical coordinates, for which we can rely on much of what we have already discussed about polar coordinates.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Triple Integrals in Cylindrical Coordinates</title>
    <p>
      To evaluate a triple integral <m>\iiint_S f(x,y,z) \, dV</m> as an iterated integral in rectangular coordinates, we use the fact that the volume element <m>dV</m> is equal to <m>dz \, dy \, dx</m>, corresponding to the volume of a small box. To evaluate a triple integral in cylindrical coordinates, we similarly must understand the volume element <m>dV</m> in cylindrical coordinates.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      In particular, we consider the volume of a solid created by a small step in each of the coordinates: <m>\Delta r</m>, <m>\Delta \theta</m>, <m>\Delta z</m>. <xref ref="fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-cyl_vol_element"/> shows an example of such a solid. You should recognize the shaded area in the <m>xy</m>-plane as the area element used for double integrals in polar coordinates. Recall that <m>\Delta A</m> was <m>\frac{1}{2}(r_{i+1}+r_i) \Delta r \ \Delta \theta</m>. Since <m>z</m> is the perpendicular height of our solid, its volume is the product of the base area and the height:
      <me>
        \Delta V = \Delta A \ \Delta z = \frac{(r_{i+1}+r_i)}{2} \Delta r \, \Delta \theta \, \Delta z
      </me>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-cyl_vol_element">
      <caption>A cylindrical box</caption>
      <interactive label="interactive-fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-cyl_vol_element" platform="sage" width="91%" aspect="1:1">
        <description>
          <p>
            A three-dimensional plot of a cylindrical <q>box</q>. In the <m>xy</m>-plane, a region is depicted. This region is bounded by two rays in the first quadrant emanating from the origin withe the angle between the rays marked <m>\Delta \theta</m>. The region in the plane is also bounded by two circles centered at the origin. Positioned above this region is a three-dimensional solid. The top and bottom of the solid are the same shape as the region in the plane with the portion of one of the rays that goes between the circles having label <m>\Delta r</m>. The vertical side of the solid is labeled <m>\Delta z</m> and the curved surface of the solid farther from the <m>z</m>-axis is labeled <m>r\, \Delta\theta</m>.
          </p>
        </description>
        <slate surface="sage">
          <xi:include href="interacts/cylindrical-vol.txt" parse="text"/>            
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Remember that as <m>\Delta r</m> shrinks, <m>\frac{(r_{i+1}+r_i)}{2}</m> approaches the <m>r</m>-coordinate of this solid. Therefore the volume element <m>dV</m> in cylindrical coordinates is <m>dV = r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta</m>.
    </p>
    <p>  
      Because we can think of cylindrical coordinates as polar coordinates plus <m>z</m>, slicing the projection of a solid onto the <m>xy</m>-plane into a <xref ref="radiallysimple" text="custom">radially simple</xref> or <xref ref="angsimple" text="custom">angularly simple</xref> description provides two of the bounds of an iterated integral used to evaluate the triple integral. Completing the description requires also providing inequalities for <m>z</m>. Finally, since the <m>z</m>-coordinate in cylindrical coordinates is the same as in rectangular coordinates, writing the integrand in cylindrical coordinates requires only converting the first two coordinates to polar coordinates using the equations <m>x=r\cos(\theta)</m> and <m>y=r\sin(\theta)</m>. We summarize this below.
    </p>
    
    <assemblage xml:id="Triple-integral-cylindrical">
      <title>Triple integrals in cylindrical coordinates</title>
      <p>
        Given a continuous function <m>f = f(x,y,z)</m> over a region <m>S</m> in <m>\R^3</m>,
        <me>
          \iiint_S f(x,y,z) \, dV = \iiint_S f(r\cos(\theta), r\sin(\theta), z) \, r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        The latter expression is an <term>iterated integral in cylindrical coordinates</term>.<idx><h>iterated integral</h><h>cylindrical coordinates</h></idx>
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    
    
    
    <p>
      While the volume element and the conversion of the integrand are done exactly the same for every triple integral written in cylindrical coordinates, the task of writing an iterated integral in cylindrical coordinates requires us to slice the particular region in terms of simple bounds on <m>\theta</m>, <m>r</m>, and <m>z</m>. In the following activity, we explore how to do this in several situations where cylindrical coordinates are natural and advantageous. This can be both in terms of providing simple expressions for the bounds on the variables and providing an integrand that is easier to integrate than the rectangular coodinate version would be. In most of the activities in this section, we ask you to focus on setting up the integral in the given coordinate system and do not ask you to evaluate the integral. Most of the insight in working in cylindrical and spherical coordinates comes from setting up the integrals. Once you have done that, you should be able to recognize how you would be able to evaluate the integral with a modest amount of work, but we will usually direct you to not complete that evaluation.
    </p>
    
    <worksheet>
      <activity workspace="1.5in" xml:id="act-mult_ints-cylsphere-cyl">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            In this activity, we will work with a few triple integrals and look at the advantages of cylindrical coordinates for the iterated integral calculation.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Let <m>S</m> be the solid bounded above by the graph of <m>z = x^2+y^2</m> and below by the unit disk in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The projection of the solid <m>S</m> onto the <m>xy</m>-plane is a disk. Describe this disk using inequalities in polar coordinates.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Write inequalities in cylindrical coordinates that describe the solid <m>S</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Write an iterated integral whose value gives the volume of <m>S</m>. <alert>You do not need to evaluate this integral.</alert>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                Since <m>x^2+y^2=r^2</m> in cylindrical coordinates, our limits on <m>z</m> will be <m>0 \leq z \leq r^2</m>. Thus, an iterated integral in cylindrical coordinates that gives the volume of <m>S</m> is
                <me>
                  \int \int \int_S 1 \, dV = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_0^1 \int_0^{r^2} (1) r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta
                </me>
                Now
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_0^1 \int_0^{r^2} r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_0^1  rz \restrict{0}^{r^2} \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_0^1 r^3 \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{r^4}{4} \restrict{0}^1 \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{4} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Suppose the density of the solid cone bounded above by <m>r = 1 - z</m> and below by <m>z = 0</m>, is given by <m>\delta(r, \theta, z) = z</m>. A picture of the cone is shown below. Set up an iterated integral in cylindrical coordinates that gives the mass of the cone. <alert>You do not need to evaluate this integral.</alert>
            </p>
            
            <interactive label="int-fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-cone" platform="sage" width="91%" aspect="1:1">
              <description>
                <p>
                  A three-dimensional plot of the solid bounded above by the cylindrical cone <m>r = 1-z</m> and below by the <m>xy</m>-plane. The tip of the cone is at the point <m>(0,0,1)</m>, and the base of the cone in the <m>xy</m>-plane is a circle centered at the origin.
                </p>
              </description>
              <slate surface="sage">
                var('r,s,t,x,y,z')
                xscale=1.5;yscale=1.5;zscale=1.5;
                plot2=arrow((0,0,0),(xscale,0,0),color="black",opacity=0.5,width=1)+text3d("x",(xscale+0.15,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,yscale+0.15,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,zscale+0.15),fontsize=30)
                plot2+=arrow((0,0,0),(0,yscale,0),color="black",opacity=0.5,width=1)+arrow((0,0,0),(0,0,zscale),color="black",opacity=0.5,width=1)
                plot2+=parametric_plot3d((r*cos(t),r*sin(t),1-r),(r,0,1),(t,0,2*pi),color="lightblue")
                plot2+=parametric_plot3d((r*cos(t),r*sin(t),0),(r,0,1),(t,0,2*pi),color="lightblue")
                plot2              
              </slate>
            </interactive>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Recall that mass is the integral of density, so the mass of the cone is
              <me>
                \int \int \int_S \delta(r, \theta, z) \, dV
              </me>.
              The cone is bounded below by the <m>xy</m>-plane and above by the surface <m>r=1-z</m>. If we integrate with respect to <m>z</m> first, then the limits on <m>z</m> are <m>0 \leq z \leq 1-r</m>. When can project the surface into the <m>xy</m>-plane as shown in the image to find the limits on <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m>. Note than when <m>z=0</m> we have <m>r=1</m>, so the projection is a circle with radius centered at the origin. Therefore, the mass of the cone given as an iterated integral is
              <me>
                \int \int \int_S \delta(r, \theta, z) \, dV = \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^1 \int_0^{1-r} zr \, dz \, dr \, d\theta
              </me>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Write an iterated integral expression in cylindrical coordinates whose value is the volume of the solid bounded below by the cone <m>z = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> and above by the cone <m>z = 4 - \sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m>. A picture is shown below. <alert>You do not need to evaluate this integral.</alert>
            </p>
              <interactive label="interactive-fig-mult_ints-cylspher-cones_combining" platform="sage" width="91%" aspect="1:1">
                <description>
                  <p>
                    A solid in three-dimensional space. The bottom boundary of the solid is a cone about the <m>z</m>-axis with its tip at the origin. The top boundary of the solid is a cone about the <m>z</m>-axis with its tip at the point <m>(0,0,4)</m>. The cones intersect at a circular shape parallel to the <m>xy</m>-plane.
                  </p>
                </description>
                <slate surface="sage">
                  var('r,s,t,x,y,z')
                  xscale=2.5;yscale=2.5;zscale=4.5
                  plot3=arrow((0,0,0),(xscale,0,0),color="black",opacity=0.5,width=1)+text3d("x",(xscale+0.15,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,yscale+0.15,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,zscale+0.15),fontsize=30)
                  plot3+=arrow((0,0,0),(0,yscale,0),color="black",opacity=0.5,width=1)+arrow((0,0,0),(0,0,zscale),color="black",opacity=0.5,width=1)
                  plot3+=parametric_plot3d((r*cos(t),r*sin(t),4-r),(r,0,2),(t,0,2*pi),color="lightblue")
                  plot3+=parametric_plot3d((r*cos(t),r*sin(t),r),(r,0,2),(t,0,2*pi),color="lightblue")
                  plot3              
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              In cylindrical coordinates the cones are <m>z=r</m> and <m>z=4-r</m>. So we have <m>r \leq z \leq 4-r</m>. Now <m>z=r</m> and <m>z=4-r</m> intersect when <m>r = 4-r</m> or when <m>r=2</m>. So the projection of this solid in the <m>xy</m>-plane is the disk <m>0 \leq r \leq 2</m> and <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>. So an iterated integral in cylindrical coordinates that gives the volume of this solid is
              <me>
                \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^2 \int_{r}^{4-r} r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </activity>
    </worksheet>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection>
    <title>Triple Integrals in Spherical Coordinates</title>
    <p>
      Similar to rectangular and cylindrical coordinates, when working in spherical coordinates we usually write <m>\rho</m> as a function of <m>\theta</m> and <m>\phi</m>. This is a natural analog to polar coordinates, where the distance from the origin in the plane is often expressed as a function of <m>\theta</m>. In spherical coordinates, writing <m>\rho</m> as a function of <m>\theta</m> and <m>\phi</m> allows us to represent distance from the origin as a function of two key angles.
    </p>
    <p>
      A triple integral <m>\iiint_S f(x,y,z) \, dV</m> in spherical coordinates can be evaluated as an iterated integral once we understand the volume element <m>dV</m>. <xref ref="fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-Spherical_Vol_Element"/> illustrates a spherical <q>box</q> generated by a small change in each of the <m>\rho</m>, <m>\theta</m>, and <m>\phi</m> coordinates. A conceptual description for where the volume element comes from is given in the proof to <xref ref="keyidea-Triple-integral-spherical"/>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-Spherical_Vol_Element">
      <caption>A spherical box</caption>
      <interactive label="interactive-F_11_8_Spherical_Vol_Element" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <description>
          <p>
            A three-dimensional plot of a spherical <q>box</q>. In the <m>xy</m>-plane, a region is depicted. This region is bounded by two rays in the first quadrant emanating from the origin withe the angle between the rays marked <m>\Delta \theta</m>. The region in the plane is also bounded by two circles centered at the origin. Positioned above this region is a three-dimensional solid. Four sides of the solid are portions of rays emanating from the origin. One of these sides is labeled <m>\Delta\rho</m>. The faces of the solid perpendicular to the rays are patches of spheres centered at the origin.
          </p>
        </description>
        <slate surface="sage">
          <xi:include href="interacts/spherical-vol.txt" parse="text"/>
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <proposition xml:id="keyidea-Triple-integral-spherical">
      <title>Triple integrals in spherical coordinates</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The volume element for spherical coordinates is <m>dV= \rho^2 \sin(\phi) \, d\rho \, d\theta \, d\phi</m>. Given a continuous function <m>f = f(x,y,z)</m> over a region <m>S</m> in <m>\R^3</m>, the triple integral <m>\iiint_S f(x,y,z) \, dV</m> can be written in spherical coordinates as
          <me>
            \iiint_S f(\rho\sin(\phi)\cos(\theta), \rho \sin(\phi) \sin(\theta), \rho \cos(\phi)) \, \rho^2 \sin(\phi) \, d\rho \, d\theta \, d\phi 
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The latter expression is an <term>iterated integral in spherical coordinates</term><idx><h>iterated integral</h><h>spherical coordinates</h></idx>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          To find the volume element <m>dV</m> in spherical coordinates, we must understand how to determine the volume of a spherical box of the form <m>\rho_1 \leq \rho \leq \rho_2</m> (with <m>\Delta \rho = \rho_2-\rho_1)</m>, <m>\phi_1 \leq \phi \leq \phi_2</m> (with <m>\Delta \phi = \phi_2-\phi_1</m>), and <m>\theta_1 \leq \theta \leq \theta_2</m> (with <m>\Delta \theta = \theta_2-\theta_1</m>). An illustration of such a box is given in <xref ref="fig-mult_ints-cylsphere-Spherical_Vol_Element">Figure</xref>. This spherical box is more complicated than the cylindrical box we encountered earlier. Rather than computing the volume <m>\Delta V</m>directly, we will focus on approximating it. We can approximate the volume <m>\Delta V</m> of this spherical box by the volume of a box in rectangular coordinates whose sides have the lengths of the sides of the spherical box. The three sides we will use are highlighted in the figure.
        </p>
        <p>
          Along the red side, <m>\rho</m> changes while <m>\theta</m> and <m>\phi</m> are constant. The length of the red side is simply the change in <m>\rho</m>, as indicated by the label <m>\Delta \rho</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Along the green side, <m>\phi</m> changes while <m>\theta</m> and <m>\rho</m> are constant. To focus our analysis, we plot only the view looking along the plane <m>\theta=\theta_0</m> in <xref ref="t0face"/>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="t0face">
          <caption>A plot of the face of the volume element with <m>\theta=\theta_0</m></caption>
          <image width="60%" >
            <description>
              <p>
                A plot of a region in the plane. The plot is in the first quadrant and includes two rays emanating from the origin. The angle between the rays is marked <m>\Delta \theta</m>. The region is bounded by these rays and the circles of radius <m>\rho_0\lt \rho_1</m> centered at the origin. The portion of one of the rays that bounds the region is labeled <m>\Delta\rho</m>. The portion of the circular arc of radius <m>\rho_1</m> that bounds the region is labeled <m>s_1</m>.
              </p>
            </description><sageplot label="img-t0face">
              var('x,y,t,s')
              r1=1;r2=1.5;t1=0.6;t2=1;
              plot5=line([(r1*cos(t2),r1*sin(t2)),(0,0),(r1*cos(t1),r1*sin(t1))],color="gray",thickness=2,axes=True,ticks=[[],[]])
              dt=(t2-t1)/25
              p1=[(r1*cos(t2-i*dt),r1*sin(t2-i*dt)) for i in range(26)]
              p2=[(r2*cos(t1+i*dt),r2*sin(t1+i*dt)) for i in range(26)]
              pp=p1+p2
              plot5+=polygon(pp,color="gray",edgecolor="black",thickness=3,zorder=2)
              plot5+=parametric_plot((0.4*cos(t),0.4*sin(t)),(t,t1,t2),color="black",thickness=2)+text("$\\Delta \\phi$",(0.35,0.35),color="black",fontsize=20)
              plot5+=parametric_plot((r1*cos(t),r1*sin(t)),(t,t1-0.5,t2+0.5),color="gray",thickness=3,linestyle="--",zorder=1)
              plot5+=parametric_plot((r2*cos(t),r2*sin(t)),(t,t1-0.5,t2+0.5),color="gray",thickness=3,linestyle="--",zorder=1)
              plot5+=text("$\\rho_0$",(r1*cos(t1),r1*sin(t1)-0.1),fontsize=20,color="gray")
              plot5+=text("$\\rho_1$",(r2*cos(t1),r2*sin(t1)-0.1),fontsize=20,color="gray")
              plot5+=text("$\\Delta \\rho$",((r1+r2)/2*cos(t2)-0.1,(r1+r2)/2*sin(t2)+0.05),fontsize=20,color="black")
              plot5+=text("$s_1$",(r2*cos((t1+t2)/2)+0.05,r2*sin((t1+t2)/2)+0.05),fontsize=20,color="black")
              plot5+=parametric_plot((r2*cos(t),r2*sin(t)),(t,t1,t2),color="green",thickness=3)
              plot5                  
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          This is the same kind of picture as we used when looking at the area element in polar coordinates. The length of the green curve labeled <m>s_1</m> is <m>\rho_1 \Delta\phi</m> by the same type of argument used in polar coordinates:
          <me> (\text{fraction of circle})(\text{circumference of circle})=\left(\frac{\Delta\phi}{2\pi}\right)\left(2\pi \rho_1 \right)= \rho_1 \Delta\phi</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Along the blue side, <m>\theta</m> changes while <m>\rho</m> and <m>\phi</m> are constant. In other words, the blue curve consists of <m>x=\rho_1 \sin(\phi_0) \cos(\theta), y= \rho_1 \sin(\phi_0), z=\rho_1 \cos(\phi_0)</m> which corresponds to a circle of radius <m>\rho_1 \sin(\phi_0)</m> parallel to the <m>xy</m>-plane and positioned at <m>z=\rho_1 \cos(\phi_0)</m>. We can use the same type of argument as above that arc length of a curve corresponding to an angular change of <m>\Delta \theta</m> along a circle of radius <m>\rho_1 \sin(\phi_0)</m> is <m>\rho_1 \sin(\phi_0) \Delta \theta</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Remember that for very small changes in the coordinates, the difference between the values of the coordinates used shrinks. For example, we are in the setting where <m>\rho=0 \approx \rho_1 \approx \rho</m>. By multiplying the lengths of the sides of the spherical box, we obtain an approximation of its volume:
          <me>\Delta V \approx \left(\Delta\rho\right) \left(\rho \,  \Delta\phi \right)\left(\rho \sin(\phi) \, \Delta\theta \right) = \rho^2 \sin(\phi) \Delta\phi \, \Delta\theta \, \Delta\rho</me>
          This leads us to the volume element in spherical coordinates
          <md>
            dV = \rho^2\sin(\phi)\, d\phi\, d\theta\, d\rho
          </md>.
          
        </p>
        <p>
          The conversion of the integrand is straightforward because <m>x= \rho\sin(\phi)\cos(\theta), y=\rho \sin(\phi) \sin(\theta), z=\rho \cos(\phi) </m> does not require interpretation based on the coordinates used.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
    
    <p>
      To complete the setup of an iterated integral in spherical coordinates, we must determine the limits of integration in <m>\phi</m>, <m>\theta</m>, and <m>\rho</m>. The process is similar to other coordinate systems. The central idea in this process will be to fix all but one coordinate and give the same bounding functions for the remaining coordinate, then project onto the remaining coordinates and repeat this process.
    </p>
    
    <worksheet>
      <activity workspace="1.5in" xml:id="act-mult_ints-cylspher-spherical">
        <task xml:id="task-mult_ints-cylspher-spherical-sphere_volume">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Set up <alert>and evaluate</alert> an iterated integral in spherical coordinates to determine the volume of a sphere of radius <m>a</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The sphere of radius <m>a</m> is expressed in spherical coordinates by <m>\rho=a</m>. Recall that the volume of a solid <m>S</m> is given by
              <me>
                \int \int \int_S \, dV
              </me>.
              Thus, the volume of a sphere of radius <m>a</m> can be calculated as an iterated integral as follows:
              <md>
                <mrow>\int \int \int_S \, dV \amp = \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^{\pi} \int_0^{a} \rho^2 \sin(\phi) \, d\rho \, d\phi \, d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^{\pi} \left[\frac{\rho^3}{3} \sin(\phi) \right]\restrict{0}^a  \, d\phi \, d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^{\pi} \frac{a^3}{3} \sin(\phi) \, d\phi \, d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \int_0^{2\pi} \left[-\frac{a^3}{3} \cos(\phi)\right]\restrict{0}^{\pi} \, d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \int_0^{2\pi} 2\frac{a^3}{3} \, d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \frac{4}{3}\pi a^3</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="task-mult_ints-cylspher-spherical-sphere_minus_cone">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Write an iterated integral in spherical coordinates whose value is the mass of the solid obtained by removing the cone <m>\phi=\frac{\pi}{4}</m> from the sphere <m>\rho = 2</m> if the density <m>\delta</m> at the point <m>(x,y,z)</m> is <m>\delta(x,y,z) = \sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}</m>.  An illustration of the solid is shown below. <alert>You do not need to evaluate this integral.</alert>
            </p>
          
              
              <interactive label="interactive-mult_ints-cylspher-spher_minus_cone" platform="sage" width="91%" aspect="1:1">
                <description>
                  <p>
                    A solid region in three-dimensional space. The solid consists of all of the sphere of radius <m>2</m> centered at the origin that is below the cone <m>\phi = \frac{\pi}{4}</m>. The point of this cone is at the origin, and it opens upward, meeting the sphere in a circle parallel to the <m>xy</m>-plane.
                  </p>
                </description><slate surface="sage">
                  <xi:include href="interacts/sph-cone.txt" parse="text"/>
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The limits on <m>\rho</m> are <m>0 \leq \rho \leq 2</m> and on <m>\theta</m> are <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>. To account for the cone being removed from the sphere we restrict <m>\phi</m>. The cone opens from <m>\phi = 0</m> to <m>\phi = \frac{\pi}{4}</m>, so the limits on <m>\phi</m> that remove the cone are <m>\frac{\pi}{4} \leq \phi \leq \pi</m>. Therefore, the density of the solid is found by
              <me>
                \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi} \int_0^2 \rho^3 \sin(\phi) \, d\rho \, d\phi \, d\theta
              </me>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              We conclude this activity with two questions that help you examine <em>why</em> you were asked to tackle the two parts above in spehrical coordinates.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Explain why the integral
                <md>
                  \int_{-a}^a \int_{=\sqrt{a^2-x^2}}^{\sqrt{a^2-x^2}} \int_{-\sqrt{a^2-x^2-y^2}}^{\sqrt{a^2-x^2-y^2}} 1\, dz\, dy\, dx
                </md>
                computes the volume of the sphere of radius <m>a</m>. Without evaluating this integral, write a sentence or two discussing how you think evaluating this integral would compare to evaluating the integral in <xref ref="task-mult_ints-cylspher-spherical-sphere_volume" text="type-local"/>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The solid in <xref ref="task-mult_ints-cylspher-spherical-sphere_minus_cone" text="type-local"/> is symmetric about the <m>z</m>-axis, which was a criterion that we used to describe solids that we might find convenient to describe in cylindrical coordinates. However, you were asked to use spherical coordinates. Write a couple of sentences discussing the challenges you would encounter in describing this solid in cylindrical coordinates.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </task>
        </task>
      </activity>
    </worksheet>
  </subsection>
  
  
  
  <outcomes>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The volume element <m>dV</m> in cylindrical coordinates is <m>dV = r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta</m>. Hence, a triple integral <m>\iiint_S f(x,y,z) \, dA</m> can be evaluated as the iterated integral of the form
          <me>
            \iiint_S f(r\cos(\theta), r\sin(\theta), z) \, r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>
      
      <li>
        <p>
          The volume element <m>dV</m> in spherical coordinates is <m>dV = \rho^2 \sin(\phi) \, d\rho \, d\theta \, d\phi</m>. Thus, a triple integral <m>\iiint_S f(x,y,z) \, dA</m> can be evaluated as the iterated integral of the form
          <me>
            \iiint_S f(\rho\sin(\phi)\cos(\theta), \rho \sin(\phi) \sin(\theta), \rho \cos(\phi)) \, \rho^2 \sin(\phi) \, d\rho \, d\theta \, d\phi.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </outcomes>
  <xi:include href="exercises/ez-S_multi_ints_triple_ints_cylsph.ptx"/>
  
</section>
